REST = Representational State Transfer
API  = Application Programming Interface

Spring Boot
Spring Boot is a Java framework used to build standalone, production-ready 
backend applications quickly with minimal configuration.
Spring Boot = Java + Ready-made backend setup + less configuration

Client (Browser/Postman)
        ↓
Controller
        ↓
Service
        ↓
Repository
        ↓
Database

ABOUT APIS: There area majorly two types of the apsi which are:
GET → Get data
POST → Send data

GET API:
GET API is used to retreive (fetch) the data fromm the server.
SYNTAX for GET API:
@GetMapping("/path")
public String methodName(@RequestParam datatype variable){
    return "response";
}
EX:@GetMapping("/add")
public String add(@RequestParam int a, @RequestParam int b){
    return "Result=" + (a + b);
}

Key points :
Data is sent in URL
Uses @RequestParam
Used for reading data
Simple and fast
Visible in browser/Postman URL

FLOW:Client → URL with parameters → Spring Boot → Method → Response


POST API:
POST API is usede to send data to the server (CREATE/save data).

SYNTAX:@PostMapping("/path")
public String methodName(@RequestBody ClassName object){
    return "response";
}


EXAMPLE:@PostMapping("/employee")
public String addEmployee(@RequestBody Employee emp){
    return "Name: " + emp.getName() + ", Age: " + emp.getAge();
}

JSON input(Postman):
{
  "name": "Irshad",
  "age": 22
}

KEY POINTS: Data is sent in Body
Uses @RequestBody
Used for creating/sending data
Data format = JSON
Not visible in URLYPOINTS:

FLOW:Client → JSON Body → Spring Boot → Converts to Object → Method → Response

GET → Get data
POST → Send data
Put - update data
Delete - Delete the data

Spring Boot CRUD APIs:

- @GetMapping → Read data
- @PostMapping → Create data
- @PutMapping → Update data
- @DeleteMapping → Delete data

Annotations:
- @RestController → Create REST API controller
- @RequestBody → Convert JSON to Java object
- @PathVariable → Get value from URL

Flow:
POST → Create
GET → Read
PUT → Update
DELETE → Delete

Current storage: ArrayList (in-memory)
Next step: JPA + MySQL integration

 JPA = Java Persistence API

