🧠 Exception Handling in Spring Boot (Notes)
🔹 What is Exception Handling?

Exception handling is a mechanism used to handle runtime errors gracefully instead of crashing the application or returning null/unclear responses.

🔹 Why do we need it?

Without exception handling:

API may return null
Server may crash with 500 Internal Server Error
Client does not understand the error properly

With exception handling:

We return meaningful error messages
Proper HTTP status codes (like 404, 400)
Clean and professional API response
Types of Exception Handling in Spring Boot
1. Basic Exception Handling
Using try-catch
Not commonly used in controllers
2. Custom Exception

Used to define your own error types.

Example:

EmployeeNotFoundException
InvalidInputException

👉 Used when a specific condition fails in business logic.

3. Global Exception Handling

Handled using:

@RestControllerAdvice

👉 Centralized place for handling all exceptions in the application.

🔹 Important Annotations
✔ @ExceptionHandler

Used to define which exception to handle.

@ExceptionHandler(EmployeeNotFoundException.class)
✔ @RestControllerAdvice

Used for global exception handling across all controllers.

🔹 HTTP Status Codes in Exception Handling
Status Code	Meaning
200	Success
404	Not Found
400	Bad Request
500	Server Error
🔹 Flow of Exception Handling
Request → Controller → Service → Exception occurs → Global Handler → Response sent
🔹 Real Example (Your Project)

If employee ID not found:

Instead of:

null

We return:

{
  "message": "Employee not found with id: 5"
}

With:

HTTP 404 NOT FOUND
🔹 Why it is important (Interview point)
Makes API production-ready
Improves user experience
Helps frontend understand errors properly
Very commonly asked in interviews

Exception handling = clean + controlled error response system

It makes your Spring Boot project look:
✔ Professional
✔ Industry-level
✔ Interview-ready



